UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304407606000327
KW  - Sample surveys
KW  - Selective unit nonresponse bias
AB  - Past approaches to correcting for unit nonresponse in sample surveys by re-weighting the data assume that the problem is ignorable within arbitrary subgroups of the population. Theory and evidence suggest that this assumption is unlikely to hold, and that household characteristics such as income systematically affect survey compliance. We show that this leaves a bias in the re-weighted data and we propose a method of correcting for this bias. The geographic structure of nonresponse rates allows us to identify a micro compliance function, which is then used to re-weight the unit-record data. An example is given for the US Current Population Surveys, 1998–2004. We find, and correct for, a strong household income effect on response probabilities.
